Introduction
2135 001 328 0903, more commonly referred to as Roger, is the sitting President of America and the main antagonist of Fractured by Time. Elected to the position of President by the Upper Class of the country, Roger holds the beliefs of a Traditionalist. The Traditionalists are a faction of the country that believe in retaining the roles they had before the Apocalypse while oppressing others who had lower status in life before the Apocalypse.

His callus and unsympathetic personality has led many to believe that he is closer to a dictator for those in the lower classes than a president. Roger is known for his disdain for those of the lower class and harsh treatment of his staff with a middle class background. Roger spends his free time playing chess with his close friend and right-hand man, Edgar. Roger is also known to spend his time fundraising and campaigning among the higher class in an attempt to gain favor for the investment into WISDOM.
WISDOM is said to have a very close tie to both the president and the government, with Joanne, the CEO of WISDOM, often seen entering the office of the president.
Roger has been the sitting President of America for 10 years and was elected in 2162 AD.

Appearance
An imposing man with a height well above the average man, his skin is pale white. His hair is dyed to a dark blue color and cut at a short trim length. His most striking feature is his bright red eyes which seem to give a menacing nature to his visage. He is most often seen wearing a suit or formal wear and seems to prefer wearing clothing with dull colors.

Personality
Roger’s personality is a complete reflection of his outside demeanor: cold, selfish, and arrogant. Although he is a man of high intellect, he distinctly perceives the majority of people as beneath him. Roger is a germaphobe and has a predilection for clean environments. However, when Roger is around close friends like Edgar he expresses a kinder countenance. Roger only respects those he perceives to be at the same class or intelligence level as him. Roger’s selfish nature causes him to primarily act in a manner that always benefits himself. Roger’s personality often causes him to be oblivious of threats like Joanne since he does not perceive her as an equal.
